Data Visualization

#facet plot with scatterplot (with regression line) of BMI vs FEV by townname
plots <- filter(newdata, !is.na(fev) & !is.na(bmi) & !is.na(townname))
plots %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = bmi, y = fev, color=townname, position="jitter")) + 
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = bmi, y = fev, linetype = obesity_level)) +
  facet_wrap(~ obesity_level, nrow = 1)
Warning in geom_point(mapping = aes(x = bmi, y = fev, color = townname, :
Ignoring unknown aesthetics: position
`geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

It is hard to distinguish prominent patterns of towns in the graphs, as there are lots of overlapping data(even with the jitter option). However, based on first glance it seems that the more âpinkâ towns (San Dimas, Santa Maria, and Upland) have most of their values in the normal range of BMIâs. The underweight category has too few points to tell any noticeable patterns, and the overweight category seems to have an equal mix of towns.

#Stacked histograms of FEV by BMI category and FEV by smoke/gas exposure. Use different color schemes than the ggplot default.
ggplot(plots, aes(x=obesity_level, y= fev, fill =obesity_level)) +
     geom_bar(stat='identity') +
scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Dark2")

The FEV of normal obesity levels seems to be highest compared to overweight and underweight children. Upon further research, it seems that the more a person can exhale during an FEV test, the stronger their lungs. Originally, I though this was the reverse. This graph therefore makes sense, as children with âhealthierâ weights, seem to have the strongest lungs. Those underweight especially have the lowest fev, which makes sense due to their smaller bodies and potentially weaker muscles.

#Barchart of BMI by smoke/gas exposure

ggplot(plots, aes(x=obesity_level, y= smoke_gas_exposure, fill= obesity_level)) +
     geom_bar(stat='identity')

Most of the data in the graphs falls under the normal weight category, meaning children with normal obesity levels have the highest counts of second hand smoke and gas stove emissions. Although there seems to be a large difference between normal and any other obesity level, further significant testing is required to make any official statement of association.

#Statistical summary graphs of FEV by BMI and FEV by smoke/gas exposure category
l <- plots%>%
  ggplot() + 
    stat_summary(mapping = aes(x = obesity_level, y = fev),
    fun.min = min,
    fun.max = max,
    fun = median)
l

There seems to be a difference between underweight vs.Â FEV compared to the other BMI categories, as it is lower than the other obesity levels. Additionally, it seems that the overweight BMI has on average, large FEV values than any other BMI category. However, this data may not be accurate to interpret because there seems to be much more children with a normal BMI, less children with an overweight BMI, and very few children with an underweight BMI. Further significance testing is required.

m <- plots%>%
  ggplot() + 
    stat_summary(mapping = aes(x = smoke_gas_exposure, y = fev),
    fun.min = min,
    fun.max = max,
    fun = median)
m

Based on the statistical summary graph, there does not seem to be much difference in FEV by smoke/gas exposure categories, as all centers seem to align with each other. However, just as with the graph above, further significance tests are required before making a definitive conclusion.

#A leaflet map showing the concentrations of PM2.5 mass in each of the CHS communities

pm.pal <-colorNumeric(c('darkgreen','goldenrod','brown'), domain=plots$pm25_mass)

leafplot <- leaflet(plots) %>% 
  # The looks of the Map
  addProviderTiles('CartoDB.Positron') %>% 
  # Some circles
  addCircles(
    lat = ~lat, lng=~lon,
                                                  # HERE IS OUR PAL!
    label = ~paste0(round(pm25_mass)), color = ~ pm.pal(pm25_mass),
    opacity = 1, fillOpacity = 1
    ) %>%
  # And a pretty legend
  addLegend('bottomleft', pal=pm.pal, values=plots$pm25_mass,
          title='PM 2.5 Concentration in CHS Communities', opacity=1)
leafplot

The map shows that the concentration levels of pm 2.5 mass are higher near a more largely populated and urban locations of Los Angeles. This makes sense given that pm 2.5 comes from heavy pollutant such as power plants, and car emissions. Locations with lower levels of pm 2.5 are less populated areas that are in more natural settings (in mountainous regions).

#Choose a visualization to examine whether PM2.5 mass is associated with FEV
plots%>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = pm25_mass, y = fev)) +
  geom_point( position="jitter") + 
  geom_smooth(method = lm, se = FALSE, col = "black")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

The linear regression line depicted above seems to denote that FEV slightly decreases as pm 2.5 increases. This line is not steep, and almost horizontal however. Although the pm25_mass variable was numeric, the graph above seems to show that its values are grouped within distinct numbers. Due to this, I have created a new categorical variable for pm2.5 mass levels, and will interpret its graph

plots <- mutate (plots, pm25levels = ifelse(pm25_mass < 10, "low", 
                                            ifelse(pm25_mass>10 & pm25_mass<15, "low-mid",
                                                   ifelse(pm25_mass >15 & pm25_mass<25, "mid", "high"))))

ggplot(plots, aes(x=pm25levels, y= fev, fill= pm25levels)) +
     geom_bar(stat='identity')

With the new bar graph, we can better observe the patterns within th pm 2.5 levels compared to fev. In the bar graph, the low and mid levels seem to have the highest values of fev, and the high and low-mid seem to have smaller fev values. This corresponds to the regression line in the graph above. Next steps would be to test its signifcance.
